That’s a surprisingly good parallel to what we’ve been discussing.

For trout, the thermocline is the transition layer in a lake where temperature changes rapidly with depth. Trout often spend time near it because it’s where several important gradients intersect:

* Cool enough water for comfort.
* Adequate oxygen.
* Access to baitfish and food.
* Energy-efficient positioning.

Now look at it through your “wave / phase / shift” lens.

The trout isn’t choosing a static location.

It’s riding a cycle.

Oscillate

A trout may move up and down around the thermocline throughout the day:

* Up to feed.
* Down to recover.
* Up at dawn/dusk.
* Down during bright midday conditions.

It is literally oscillating around an energetic optimum.

Ride the Wave

When conditions are stable:

* Water temperature stable.
* Oxygen stable.
* Bait concentrated.

The trout can “ride” the thermocline for long periods because it remains the best tradeoff zone.

Fishermen often find schools stacked near a particular depth because many fish have independently found the same optimum.

Shift to a New Wave

Then something changes:

* Cold front.
* Wind turnover.
* Heavy rain.
* Seasonal progression.
* Lake turnover in fall.

The thermocline moves or disappears.

The trout don’t stubbornly stay at the old depth.

They shift to a new equilibrium.

The “wave” itself has moved.

